ce:section.ce:para:
After successfully synthesizing H-CDs aggregates, the sensing performance of H-CDs aggregates (fw of 90% (v/v)) toward VBNs was explored. First, the fluorescence response of the H-CDs aggregates to seven different VBNs, including histamine, putrescine, spermine, tyramine, cadaverine, spermidine, and ammonium hydroxide, were studied. Fig. 3
                        A showed that the H-CDs aggregates exhibited different sensitivities in detecting different VBNs, with good sensitivity for spermine and ammonium hydroxide, as confirmed by the significant decrease of the intensity ratio of two emission peaks (I615/I480). Furthermore, the fluorescence response behaviours of H-CDs aggregates to spermine and ammonium hydroxide were explored. As revealed in Fig. 3B (Ⅰ), upon increasing spermine, the PL intensity of H-CDs aggregates at 615 nm gradually decreased whereas that at 480 nm showed relatively stable emission. The PL intensity ratio I615/I480 showed a good linear correlation (R2 = 0.996) with the concentrations of spermine (0–200 μM), and the calculated limit of detection (LOD) was 7 μM (S/N = 3). For ammonium hydroxide (Fig. 3C), there was a good linear correlation (R2 = 0.997) between the PL intensity ratio I615/I480 and the concentrations of ammonium hydroxide in the range of 0–60 ppm, with a calculated LOD as low as 137 ppb (S/N = 3). In addition, the sensing system proposed in this study was compared with other existing fluorescence sensors (Table 1
                        ). Compared with other sensors, the fabricated sensors dispalyed a comparable detection range and LOD. Thus, the as-prepared H-CDs aggregates displayed a sensitive detection for spermine and ammonium hydroxide, indicating the feasibility for detecting VBNs in seafood spoilage.
